node.text:
I don't often talk about the negatives of travel, because there is so much positivity to share!  But truth be told, life of a full-time traveler is not always rainbows and ponies. 

In this video, I open up to you and share why AIRPORTS are the most stressful part of the travel experience for me.  They are the main driver for my severe anxiety -- because of all the immigration questions, checkpoints, police encounters -- while often trying to hide my identity as a YouTuber.  Because believe it or not, being a content creator (i.e. Journalist) is frowned upon in MANY countries around the world.  Like Mauritania, where I was heading when I made this video. 

Does anyone else out there feel the same anxiety about airports? I'd love to hear from you in the comments below 🙏

node.title: I’M TERRIFIED OF AIRPORTS. HERE’S WHY

node.text:
North Korea is (by a long shot) the world's most interesting country.  I visited the capital city of Pyongyang in April 2017, way back when I first got a video camera, and luckily I was able to document it.  It was a wild trip to say the least, and I'm glad that I can share my experiences with you in this video. 

Buckle up for the next 9 minutes as I take you deep inside Pyongyang to see how many things I could get for $10 USD -- I think you will be quite surprised!

node.text:
This is my final video from Iraq. I had the time of my life road tripping around this beautiful Middle Eastern country with my buddy  @wanderreds, and I hope you've enjoyed my stories there over the last 9 weeks. 

On my final day in Baghdad, I met up with my long time Iraqi friend @baderkhanamerbadran who you might know well from the many videos we shot together in Iraqi Kurdistan.  We hit the streets of Baghdad (his hometown), and tried all of the best street food that the city has to offer!  Believe it or not, we were able to try 5 dishes for just $15USD total, now that's a bargain!

Also - it's with a heavy heart to explain that 24 hours after we shot this video, there was suicide bombing in the exact same market, on the same street, during the same time of the day.  I was devastated to hear the news that 32 people lost their lives and 110 more injured.  My deepest condolences go out to all of the families and loved ones who were effected this horrible act, and I hope the city will soon return back to its glory days.

Thanks again for watching my videos, and I look forward to sharing my next stories in Dubai and Mauritania! 🇦🇪🇲🇷

Dear friends, this is my favorite video so far from Iraq!  I hope you guys will connect with this story. 

Iraq is famous for its marshlands (also known as Mesopotamian Marshes). It's a rare, aquatic landscapes in the desert, stretching hundreds of miles across Southeastern Iraq into Southwestern Iran. 

In fact, these marshes were one of the largest wetland ecosystems in the world until sadly, they were drained in the 1980s and 1990s under Saddam's rule.  However, in recent years, the marshlands are back to higher water levels and it was awarded as a UNESCO world heritage site in 2016.

I visited the Iraqi Marshlands with @wanderreds for 24 hours, and I documented the entire adventure for you to see.  I will never forget how amazing this experience was! ❤️🇮🇶

In the end, we made it in one piece and I documented the entire experience on my Gopro for you guys to see 🇮🇶😆

WELCOME TO KARBALA, IRAQ.  This is the site of the world's largest pilgrimage, where every October, over 15 MILLION Shia Muslims walk from neighboring countries to show respect to Imam Hussain's shrine (the grandson of prophet Muhammad). 

Karbala’s atmosphere is unlike any place I've ever been.  The mosques and mausoleums are STUNNING, and somehow, @wanderreds and I got special VIP access into the back room to meet with the boss... and he gave me permission to film inside Iraq’s holiest site. 

Then, we randomly got invited into a family's home where they cooked us an outstanding 10 course meal.  The hospitality in Iraq is the world’s finest!! 

If you're still reading this, just know that I love you and thanks so much for watching my videos and supporting me over the years.  I was in my happiest place, traveling through Iraq proper, and I'm just so grateful to be able to share these stories with you.  More to come soon ❤️🇮🇶🙏

The first time I heard about Babylon was in first grade -- my teacher taught me that human civilization started there, in ancient Mesopotamia.  The Babylonian civilization dates back to the 19th Century BC, and is absolutely mind blowing to be walking these grounds in 2021.  The best part is that @wanderreds and I were THE ONLY ONES THERE. 

If these ruins were in a country like Italy or Spain, then they would be the most visited sites on earth... But sadly, we are deep in the heart of Iraq, a nation that has been torn apart by war and turmoil over the last 30 years, and literally nothing is around us. 

I've been to 194 countries and I've seen a lot of cool things and places, but this ranks up there as one of the best.  It might just be number 1.  It's really hard to put into words the feeling of exploring Babylon. 

I hope that you guys enjoy this adventure and that you learn something new.  I am so grateful to have this platform and be able to share my experiences, because so few outsiders get to come here.  Thanks for watching and more coming soon from Iraq!

After wandering around #Baghdad for a few days, the real Iraqi adventure has just began... @wanderreds I road tripped to the outskirts of #Babylon - the world's first city dating back to 19th Century BC -- and we stumbled upon a MASSIVE palace that overlooks the ancient ruins. 

We parked our car, and wandered inside.  It was Saddam Hussein's former palace, which is now abandoned.  It was scary to knock down doors and crawl through shattered glass and broken bottles, but it was an experience I'll never forget.  You have to see it to believe it!

I don't often talk about the negatives of travel, because there is so much positivity to share!  But truth be told, life of a full-time traveler is not always rainbows and ponies. 

In this video, I open up to you and share why AIRPORTS are the most stressful part of the travel experience for me.  They are the main driver for my severe anxiety -- because of all the immigration questions, checkpoints, police encounters -- while often trying to hide my identity as a YouTuber.  Because believe it or not, being a content creator (i.e. Journalist) is frowned upon in MANY countries around the world.  Like Mauritania, where I was heading when I made this video. 

Does anyone else out there feel the same anxiety about airports? I'd love to hear from you in the comments below 🙏

node.text:
FLIGHTS JUST BOOKED TO MY LAST 2 COUNTRIES - Jamaica (196) and Saudi Arabia (197)! 🌏🎉 

It’s so crazy to think that 3 months from now, I will be completing a lifelong goal that I set for myself when I was a kid.  I’m feeling very grateful for the past 10 years of nonstop travel, and even if a pandemic will delay the finish line by 18 months, it’s all gonna be worth it in the end. 

If there’s one big takeaway I’ve had from my travels, it would be that ALL PEOPLE ARE THE SAME.  Regardless of race, wealth, gender, religion, ethnicity, beliefs, sexual orientation (etc) - all human beings have the same wants and needs. We all need food, water and shelter to survive.  We all want happiness and laughter.  We all cry.  We all want to love and feel loved in return.  We all need to make money to support ourselves and our families. 

It’s the interconnectedness of us all that is so beautiful and worth celebrating! 

Big announcements coming soon about my next chapter. But for now, I’m laser focused on telling the best stories in these final 2 nations and also shooting the last episodes for @drewbinskydocumentary 🙏  If you will be around Jamaica or Saudi, let me know! Or if you have any tips for story ideas, etc, I’d be so grateful.  Happy Sunday to you!

node.text:
I’m standing in an ancient Mesopotamian city called #Uruk, in present-day Southern Iraq.  In the year 3,100 BC, there was an estimated 90,000 people living here, making it the world’s largest urban area at that time.  The legendary King Gilgamesh ruled Uruk in its heyday until the city lost its significance around 2,000 BC.  Uruk remained partially inhabited until the Islamic conquest of 633-638, and since then, its been completely abandoned and left alone in the middle of the desert. 

Walking around this place is hard to comprehend.  I’m literally stepping on mosaics, cups, bowls, knives and other “household items” that I’ve only been able to see in museums.  If this site was in Italy or France (or similar), there would be a $100 ticket fee to get inside and thousands of people standing in line at the door... But this is Iraq.  Amazing sites like Uruk are left behind in the dust.  Nothing is around.  Only a gatekeeper, who was taking a nap, let us inside. 

This is my final post from Iraq (for now) and I just want to say that this country is really special and I had the time of my life on this road trip - from Baghdad to Babylon, Karbala, Najaf, Samarra, Basra, the Marshalands, Ur, Uruk and everything in between.  I hope you enjoyed my stories here and thank you to all the lovely friends I made along the way.  I will most definitely be back to continue exploring the beautiful people, culture, and history of Iraq.  Have a nice weekend everyone!

node.text:
This is my final video from Iraq. I had the time of my life road tripping around this beautiful Middle Eastern country with my buddy  @wanderreds, and I hope you've enjoyed my stories there over the last 9 weeks. 

On my final day in Baghdad, I met up with my long time Iraqi friend @baderkhanamerbadran who you might know well from the many videos we shot together in Iraqi Kurdistan.  We hit the streets of Baghdad (his hometown), and tried all of the best street food that the city has to offer!  Believe it or not, we were able to try 5 dishes for just $15USD total, now that's a bargain!

Also - it's with a heavy heart to explain that 24 hours after we shot this video, there was suicide bombing in the exact same market, on the same street, during the same time of the day.  I was devastated to hear the news that 32 people lost their lives and 110 more injured.  My deepest condolences go out to all of the families and loved ones who were effected this horrible act, and I hope the city will soon return back to its glory days.

Thanks again for watching my videos, and I look forward to sharing my next stories in Dubai and Mauritania! 🇦🇪🇲🇷

Still at a loss for words 😢 8 of my Afghan friends are currently hiding in the country, scared that they may be killed if they walk outside their front door.  One is a female activist, another is an athlete, a dancer, a photographer, a hotel manager and a few are tour guides. 

We are working around the clock to find them food, shelter and an escape route.  To anyone who is able to help donate, please see the link in my bio.  It’s run by a friend, who set up a fundraiser for our beloved Afghan friends and tour guides.  Thank you ❤️🇦🇫

Also, to all my Afghan friends out there - feel free to use this space to get your voice heard.  Share your situation, your thoughts, your concerns, and I hope that people in this community can help.  You matter.  We are all listening.  And holding our breath.

node.text:
Afghanistan is love.  Afghanistan is beauty.  Afghanistan is friendly.  Afghanistan is comfort. 

I’m truly heart broken.  Devastated. 

I’ve spent a month of my life in Afghanistan on two separate trips.  Once in 2018, the other time 10 months ago.  All 7 provinces that I visited are now controlled by the Taliban, including Kabul, which fell a few hours ago as I watched on live TV. 

The US embassy just pulled out.  The airport is closed.  Visas for Afghans to nearby countries are suspended.  The borders are seemingly locked, and it leaves me in tears. 

We are looking at a situation where over 37 million innocent Afghans — the purest, most humble people I’ve met on this planet — are in serious danger. 

Under the Taliban’s evil rule, as proven in the late 1990s -  women are given no freedoms.  They are forced into marriage, sexually abused or in many cases, stoned to death.  If you don’t follow the Taliban’s extreme rules (like dress code) you may be hung to death in a public square. 

How will people be able to go to the market to get food to feed their families?  How will they be able to study, if all schools are run by the Taliban?  How will Covid vaccines be distributed if the Taliban destroys all of the clinics (which I just read, already happened to one clinic). 

Many of you have been asking about Noor, my great friend and tour guide.  He is safe and currently hiding — trying to find an escape.  I’m also in constant communication with 8 other Afghan friends on the ground, who are all begging for help. 

I ask you kindly, please donate anything you can.  There are links in my IG stories for where you can help. 

My heart is with Afghanistan.  It truly is one of my favorite countries in the world and this situation feels personal for me. 

To all of my friends and loved ones out there - stay strong.  We are keeping you in our thoughts.  I pray that peace will prevail in this beautiful land ❤️🇦🇫
